==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Sole
<hw>Sole</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>sole</ets>, L.
<ets>solea</ets>; -- so named from its flat shape. See <er>Sole</er> of
the foot.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Any one of several
species of flatfishes of the genus <gen>Solea</gen> and allied genera of
the family <fam>Soleidae</fam>, especially the common European species
(<spn>Solea vulgaris</spn>), which is a valuable food fish.</def>
<sd>(b)</sd> <def>Any one of several American flounders somewhat
resembling the true sole in form or quality, as the California sole
(<spn>Lepidopsetta bilineata</spn>), the long-finned sole
(<spn>Glyptocephalus zachirus</spn>), and other species.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Lemon</b></col>, ⟦or⟧ <col><b>French</b></col>,
<col><b>sole</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a European species
of sole (<spn>Solea pegusa</spn>).</cd> -- <col><b>Smooth sole</b></col>
<fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the megrim.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1368 --></p>

<p><ent>Sole</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Sole
<hw>Sole</hw> <pr>(s⟦omac⟧l)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>sole</ets>, fr. L. <ets>soolea</ets> (or rather an assumed L.
<ets>sola</ets>), akin to <ets>solum</ets>round, soil, sole of the foot.
Cf. <er>Exile</er>, <er>Saloon</er>, <er>Soil</er> earth, <er>Sole</er>
the fish.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The bottom of the foot; hence, also,
rarely, the foot itself.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The dove found no rest for the <qex>sole</qex> of her foot.</q>
<rj><qau>Gen. viii. 9.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Hast wandered through the world now long a day,⟦br⟧
Yet ceasest not thy weary <qex>soles</qex> to lead.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The bottom of a shoe or boot, or the piece of
leather which constitutes the bottom.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The ⟦ldquo⟧caliga⟦rdquo⟧ was a military shoe, with a very thick
<qex>sole</qex>, tied above the instep.</q>
<rj><qau>Arbuthnot.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The bottom or lower part of anything, or that on
which anything rests in standing.</def> Specifially: <sd>(a)</sd>
<fld>(Agric.)</fld> <def>The bottom of the body of a plow; -- called
also <altname>slade</altname>; also, the bottom of a furrow.</def>
<sd>(b)</sd> <fld>(Far.)</fld> <def>The horny substance under a horse's
foot, which protects the more tender parts.</def> <sd>(c)</sd>
<fld>(Fort.)</fld> <def>The bottom of an embrasure.</def> <sd>(d)</sd>
<fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>A piece of timber attached to the lower part of
the rudder, to make it even with the false keel.</def> <au>Totten.</au>
<sd>(e)</sd> <fld>(Mining)</fld> <def>The seat or bottom of a mine; --
applied to horizontal veins or lodes.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Sole leather</b></col>, <cd>thick, strong, used for
making the soles of boots and shoes, and for other
purposes.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sole</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Sole
<hw>Sole</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Soled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Soling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To furnish with a sole; <as>as, to
<ex>sole</ex> a shoe</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sole</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Sole
<hw>Sole</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>solus</ets>, or OF.
<ets>sol</ets>, F. <ets>seul</ets> (fr. L. <ets>solus</ets>; cf. L.
<ets>sollus</ets> whole, entire. Cf. <er>Desolate</er>, <er>Solemn</er>,
<er>Solo</er>, <er>Sullen</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Being or acting
without another; single; individual; only.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The
<xex>sole</xex> son of my queen.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He, be sure . . . first and last will reign⟦br⟧
<qex>Sole</qex> king.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>Single; unmarried; <as>as, a feme
<ex>sole</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Corporation sole</b></col>. <cd>See the Note under
<er>Corporation</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Single; individual; only; alone;
solitary.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Solecism</ent>⟦br⟧
